T1  - Finite horizons, life-cycle savings, and time-series evidence on consumption
AU  - Galí, Jordi
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 26
IS  - 3
SP  - 433
EP  - 452
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/12/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(90)90006-P
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329090006P
AB  - This paper develops an explicitly aggregated life-cycle model which allows for finite horizons and declining individual labor supply. The model can generate a common upward trend in aggregate consumption, labor income, and nonhuman wealth, without relinquishing Hall's random walk at the micro level. Life-cycle factors are shown to imply that consumption changes should be (a) predictable and (b) smoother than in the infinite-horizon model. Econometric evidence using postwar U.S. data suggests that neither consumption's predictability nor its excess smoothness can be fully accounted for by life-cycle considerations.
